<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,834,1794]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,323,1554,1579]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Diakonoff)" baseAuthorityName="Diakonoff" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[647,898,1554,1579]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Scaeosopha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseusta">
<emphasis box="[647,661,1555,1579]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[675,759,1555,1578]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">pseusta</emphasis>
(Diakonoff)
</taxonomicName>
in the male genitalia, but can be separated from it by the brachia of uncus with basal half expanded to a sclerotized quadrate plate, the valvella with distal 1/7 expanded to a densely setose tuberculum, and the phallus without cornutus (
<figureCitation box="[1002,1086,1626,1650]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–42" captionStartId="18.[151,263,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[232,1344,669,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-286@18.[226,1360,637,1922]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 39–42. Male genitalia of Scaeosopha spp. 39, S. spinivalvata sp. nov., holotype, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 31023; 40, S. tuberculata sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide no. ZZW08050; 41, S. victoriensis sp. nov., holotype, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 32349; 42, S. incantata Meyrick, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 31006." pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authority="(Diakonoff)" baseAuthorityName="Diakonoff" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[1136,1390,1626,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Scaeosopha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseusta">
<emphasis box="[1136,1248,1627,1651]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">S. pseusta</emphasis>
(Diakonoff)
</taxonomicName>
, the brachia of uncus are expanded in basal 1/4, the valvella is not tuberculum distally, and the phallus bears two cornuti.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,834,1794]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,335,1735,1759]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[855,994,1734,1758]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">tuberculatus</emphasis>
= tuberculum, in reference to the distal 1/7 of the valvella expanded to a tuberculum.
</paragraph>
